.\nSEE PURCHASE TIME\nUnemployment, One Unfavorable\nAspect, Has Been Materially\nChecked.\nDespite the unsatiffactory features\nwhich still prevail, business conditions\nare somewhat more encouraging.\nSharp contrasts continue in\ndifferent trades and industries, but\nthere qre more points of *aln than\nformerly and clearer evidence that\nthe price readjustments are workins:\ntoward a revival of demand. The\nrecent favorable turn' in textile\nbranches has been extended, with\nmills in New England and elsewhere\nexpanding operations as orders begin\nto flow more freely from distributors.\nand the leather and footwear\nmarkets are experiencing a\ngradual and moderate recovery.\nSimilar indications are developing\nIn some other quarters and strengthening\nof pric#S is noted in certain\ninstances, though a comprehensive\nlist of wholesale quotations again\ndiscloses an excess of recessions.\nWhere the price yielding has apparently\nnot yet ended, as In iron\nand steel, the waiting attitude of\nbuyers persists, and this serves to\nemphasize the irregularity of the\npresent situation. The main trend\n3f late, however, has been in the\ndirection of improvement, and the\nenlarging attendance of merchants\nin many of the leading centers, and\ntheir increasing disposition to purchase.\nis a phase which gives rise\nto hopeful expectations.\nMunt Replenish Stoeks.\nWith important commitments long\nleferred, stocks of goods are beginning\nto require replenishment in\nvarious places, and the clearance\nsales in retail stores are preparing\nthe way for replacements at the\nlower prices current in primary\nchannels. While the heavy buying\nwhen prices were advancing went\nbeyond the actual need for consumption\nand made inevitable a period\nof reaction, the readjustments\n:>f recent months have enhanced the\nprospects for subsequent progress\nalong conservative and sounder\nlines. The rather extensive unemployment\nand the increased commercial\nmortality are among the unfavorable\naspects, but the spread of\nidleness has been checked in some\nindustries and the larger number\n\">f failures is not an unnatural development.\nLiquidating; Contracts.\nThere is little, if any. buying\nmovement in iron and steel, and\nurrent requirements are not sufficient\nto materially affect present\nProducing schedules Reports of a\nw of the idle pig-iron stacks resuming\noperations are heard, but\nhe mills of all but the leading inerest\nare operating on about a 25\n>er cent of capacity basis. Buyers\nire apparently withholding orders\nn anticipation of further concessions\nin the price of fupl and pig\nron and finished lines are dull. In\nill instances unfilled tonnages have\n>cen greatly reduced, and existing\nontracts are b?ing liquidated steadly.\nRail orders for fair tonnages\niave been placed recently, but autonobile\nmanufacturers are still out\n>f the market, and special steels\n?how considerable irregularity. On\nhe other hand, certain manufacurers\nof high-sbeed tool steel re>ort\nbut few cancellations and are\n(till in a position to operate to alnost\nfull capacity.\nSilk Market Firm.\nIn dry goods, production in the\nr.iil districts is increasing steadily,\nnany of the large cotton mills havng\nresumed full time operations.\n..arge distributors report that the\nvolume of business done so far this\nmonth has been above expectations\nind in some cases they have mado\nash offers for prompt deliveries\n>f standard staples. The number of\nbuyers of dry goods in New York\nit present is larger than for many\nrears at this season, and in some\nnstances selling agents have deem d\nit advisable to withdraw their\n>fferings of standard cotton goods\nifter having sold ahead for sixty\nlays. Sales of print cloths at Fall\nliver during the past week were\nleavier than at any time dufing\n:he past six months. Knit goods\nnanufacturers report better demand\nor their products and a considerable\nimprovement has been noted\nn the silk trade, the raw silk market\nbeing firmer as a result.\nHides Sell Well.\nIn the hide and leather markets\nl well grounded belief prevails that\nralues have at last reached a level\nhat will permit of no further reluctions.\nLarger sales of hides were\neported during the past week and\nalfsklns continued to show\ntrength. In regard to calfskins,\nlowever, it should be noted that\nluring the slump in the market\nhese showed a drop in price out of\nill proportion to other competing\ngrades. At one time calf was on\nilmost the same level as its artitiial\nsubstitute. Shoe manufacturers\n,re resuming operations slowly and\nndependent tanners are inclined to\nalk somewhat higher prices. Leaher\nstocks are still reported to be\nairly large, the majority of orders\n>laced by shoe manufacturers being\nor small quantities needed In filing\nsmall orders that have already\n>een booked. Shoe manufacturers\ntill hesitate to produce for stock\n?urposes and are expected to main-i\nain this attitude until there is some\neflnite indication that the present I\nuying spur on the part of jobbers\nnd retailers will continue.\nWould Help Chinese.\nJ. H. Defrees. president of Chamer\nof Commerce of United States,\nias issued an appeal to business\nnen of United States to give genrously\ntowards relief of 16,000,000\ntarvlng Chinese. Mr. Defrees Is a\nnember, of committee of 130 men\ntamed by President Wilson to died\nrelief work in this country.\nBUS\nd Bvery 1\ni trial, Bui\"\nFIDELITY COMI\nFORMER 1\ni _____\nin^Hp%:\n-;v\nFRANKLIN I\nCandidate (or Vice Preaident on\nAssistant Secretary of the Nav\nof the Fidelity and Deposit Cc\nRoosevelt is another of the\nformed connection with leading\ntermination of their service in\nDENIES HNANC1NG\nBALTIC RAILROAE\nHead of Baldwin Compan;\nSays Works Are Not Interested\nin Poland.\nPHILADELPHIA. Jan. 23?Sam\nuel M. Vauclain. president of th\nBaldwin Locomotive Company de\nnied emphatically published cabli\nreports from Paris that the BalcJ\nwin company is financing a hug\ndeal between Poland, Rumania am\nBulgaria for the construction of J\nrailroad from ths Baltic to th\nBlack Sea.\n\"We have enough to do,\" *a!<\nMr Vauclain. \"to lock after ou\nbusiness in building locomotives fo\nthis country. We are not puttim\nour money into financing railroad:\nin countries where conditions an\nso unsettled as they are in Polarn\nand the other countries.\"\nRevocation Right Sustained.\nThe Department of Agricultun\nannounces that the right of th\"\nSecretary, under section 5 of Level\nact. to revoke licenses of livestocl\ncommission houses for failure to re\nturn to customers moneys found t<\nhave been charged in excess o\nmoneys actually spent for feedini\nstock hfId for sale in their yardi\nwas upheld in opinion handed dowi\nJanuary 12 by Judge Evans, sittinf\nin U. S. District Court of Norther*\ndistrict of Illinois.\nRetailers Are Buying.\nUnited Press associations reporl\nfrom New York January 20 that W\nP. H. Koelsch, president of Natlona\nAssociation of Credit Men. says retailers\nhave resumed buying, fore\ncasting a return to normal production.\nMr. Koelsch. who is also pres\nident of New Netherlands Bank\nsays that buyer* apparently are satisfied\nthat -wholesale prices hav<\nbetn reduced as far as possible under\npresent conditions.\nOhio Tuec\nVacuum Cleaner\nKikes American Homes Dirtiest, Thirties*.\nSpotless.\nAt Most Zlectrie Stores. Ei.it Terms.\nJ. Watson Terhune, Distributor\nFt. TT06. 1410 H St. IV. W.\nHamilton Dairy\nWm. R. Selecman Co.\n1436 P Street N. W.\nPhone Franklin 6936\nWash\", D. C.\n600 BOOKS STORAGE wo ,001,s\nHousehold foods, merchandise\nHou3?-to-house moving.\nSuburban and long distance haulinf,\nPACKIXG-CRATIKG-SHIPIMNG\nExpert Work. Fair prioet. Estimates.\nWINTER Rl lLDIMu STORAGK\nrbou m. mt, i43i tj at. w.\nRiley School of\nSurgery ar\nTwo to Foar-Year Connie*. Dr\npraetle. Ready to Praetl\nExpert Facultj\nYon Can Ears\nDay and Mfht Claai\nA Coarse ia Eagrll\nFree Clinlea at 6i3? p. na. Mon.\nWrite or Pkoae f